Snowflake Views - Complete Notes
What is a View?

A View in Snowflake is a virtual table created from a SQL query.

A view does not store actual data (except Materialized Views).
It stores only the SQL definition and metadata.
When queried, Snowflake executes the underlying query and returns the latest data from the base tables.
Example
CREATE VIEW emp_view AS
SELECT
    emp_id,
    emp_name,
    salary
FROM employees;

Querying the view:

SELECT * FROM emp_view;

Snowflake internally executes:

SELECT
    emp_id,
    emp_name,
    salary
FROM employees;
Why Use Views?

Views are commonly used for:

Simplifying complex queries
Data security
Data abstraction
Reusability
Reporting and dashboards
Restricting access to sensitive columns
Example

Base Table:

employees
---------
emp_id
emp_name
salary
ssn

Create a public-facing view:

CREATE VIEW employee_public AS
SELECT
    emp_id,
    emp_name,
    salary
FROM employees;

Users can access salary information without seeing SSN data.

Types of Views in Snowflake
1. Standard View

A Standard View stores only the query definition.

Example
CREATE VIEW sales_view AS
SELECT *
FROM sales
WHERE amount > 1000;
Characteristics
Stores metadata only
No physical data storage
Always returns latest data
No additional storage cost
Advantages
Easy to create
Good for security
Simplifies reporting
Disadvantages
Query executes every time
Complex views may impact performance
2. Secure View

A Secure View provides an additional layer of security.

Example
CREATE SECURE VIEW employee_secure AS
SELECT
    emp_id,
    emp_name,
    salary
FROM employees;
Features
Hides underlying implementation details
Protects metadata exposure
Recommended for data sharing
Improves security for external consumers
Use Cases
External customer access
Snowflake Data Sharing
Sensitive business data
3. Materialized View

A Materialized View physically stores precomputed query results.

Example
CREATE MATERIALIZED VIEW mv_sales AS
SELECT
    product_id,
    SUM(amount) AS total_sales
FROM sales
GROUP BY product_id;
Characteristics
Stores actual query results
Faster query performance
Consumes storage
Automatically maintained by Snowflake
Advantages
Fast aggregations
Faster dashboard queries
Reduced query computation
Disadvantages
Additional storage cost
Some SQL limitations
Materialized View Maintenance in Snowflake

Unlike many databases, Snowflake automatically updates Materialized Views.

Example

Base Table:

product_id | amount
-----------+-------
101        | 100
101        | 200

Materialized View:

product_id | total_sales
-----------+------------
101        | 300

Insert new data:

INSERT INTO sales VALUES (101,50);

Snowflake automatically updates the Materialized View.

Result:

product_id | total_sales
-----------+------------
101        | 350
Important

No manual refresh is required.

Snowflake → Automatic Refresh
Materialized Views in Other Databases
PostgreSQL

Requires manual refresh.

REFRESH MATERIALIZED VIEW mv_sales;
Oracle

Supports:

ON COMMIT Refresh
ON DEMAND Refresh
Scheduled Refresh

Example:

EXEC DBMS_MVIEW.REFRESH('MV_SALES');
MySQL

No native Materialized Views.

SQL Server

Uses Indexed Views instead of Materialized Views.

4. Recursive View

Used for hierarchical or tree-structured data.

Example

Employee Hierarchy

CEO
├── Manager1
│   ├── Employee1
│   └── Employee2
└── Manager2
    └── Employee3
Example
CREATE RECURSIVE VIEW org_hierarchy AS
WITH RECURSIVE cte AS
(
    SELECT
        emp_id,
        manager_id,
        emp_name
    FROM employees
    WHERE manager_id IS NULL

    UNION ALL

    SELECT
        e.emp_id,
        e.manager_id,
        e.emp_name
    FROM employees e
    JOIN cte
      ON e.manager_id = cte.emp_id
)
SELECT *
FROM cte;
Use Cases
Organization charts
Folder structures
Product categories
Bill of Materials (BOM)
View vs Materialized View
Feature	Standard View	Materialized View
Stores Data	No	Yes
Stores Metadata	Yes	Yes
Query Performance	Normal	Faster
Storage Cost	Minimal	Additional Storage
Query Recalculated	Every Time	No
Automatic Maintenance	N/A	Yes
Best For	Security & Abstraction	Performance Optimization
What Does "Stores Only Metadata" Mean?

When creating:

CREATE VIEW emp_view AS
SELECT
    emp_id,
    emp_name
FROM employees;

Snowflake stores:

✅ View Name

✅ Owner

✅ Creation Date

✅ SQL Definition

✅ Column Information

Snowflake does NOT store:

❌ Employee Records

❌ Actual Data Rows

Actual data remains in the underlying table.

What Happens if the Base Table Changes?
Adding a Column
ALTER TABLE employees
ADD department VARCHAR;

View continues to work.

Dropping a Referenced Column
ALTER TABLE employees
DROP COLUMN emp_name;

View breaks because the column no longer exists.

Renaming a Referenced Column
ALTER TABLE employees
RENAME COLUMN emp_name TO employee_name;

View breaks.

Dropping the Table
DROP TABLE employees;

View remains in metadata but becomes unusable.

Nested Views

A view can reference another view.

Example
CREATE VIEW v_emp AS
SELECT *
FROM employees;
CREATE VIEW v_high_salary AS
SELECT *
FROM v_emp
WHERE salary > 100000;
Advantages
Reusable logic
Modular design
Disadvantages
Harder debugging
Potential performance impact
Security with Views

Instead of granting access directly to tables:

GRANT SELECT ON TABLE employees TO ROLE analyst;

Organizations often grant access to views:

GRANT SELECT ON VIEW employee_public TO ROLE analyst;

Benefits:

Better security
Controlled access
Hides sensitive information
Useful Snowflake View Commands
List All Views
SHOW VIEWS;
Describe a View
DESC VIEW emp_view;

or

DESCRIBE VIEW emp_view;

Shows:

Column names
Data types
Metadata
Get View Definition
SELECT GET_DDL('VIEW', 'EMP_VIEW');

Returns:

CREATE VIEW EMP_VIEW AS
...

Useful for:

Debugging
Migration
Reverse Engineering
Important
What is a View?

A virtual table created from a SQL query that stores metadata and query definition rather than actual data.

What is a Materialized View?

A database object that physically stores query results for faster retrieval.

Does Snowflake Materialized View Require Manual Refresh?

No.

Snowflake automatically maintains Materialized Views when underlying data changes.

Difference Between View and Materialized View?
View	Materialized View
Stores Query Only	Stores Query Result
No Storage Cost	Consumes Storage
Query Runs Every Time	Faster Retrieval
Always Current	Automatically Maintained
Why Use Secure Views?

To prevent users from accessing underlying implementation details and improve data security during data sharing.

Key Takeaways
Views are virtual tables.
Standard Views store metadata only.
Secure Views provide enhanced security.
Materialized Views store precomputed results.
Snowflake automatically maintains Materialized Views.
Recursive Views help model hierarchical data.
Views are widely used for security, reporting, and abstraction.
Materialized Views are primarily used for performance optimization.
SHOW VIEWS, DESC VIEW, and GET_DDL() are essential Snowflake commands for working with views.
